&quot;Garden Party&quot;<br><br>
A poem by Robert H. Dirr Jr.<br><br>
I used to mingle with the remains of my dead friends at the<br>
Winton Cafe or Poor Michael's Drinkery or even in the<br>
Solitude of my room with a bottle of Captain Jack and a<br>
Pipe filled with the good stuff, but those days have died.<br><br>
I though about my bitching ex-wife but it was more depressing<br>
Than picking body parts out of a tree, like so many apples,<br>
Or visiting the family of a friend who died before his time.<br>
Still, I try to deal with the subjects I have to deal with.<br><br>
Blood and guts can be tedious, but between the lines are subtle<br>
Messages that need to be heard and understood if for no one but<br>
Myself.  You see, my garden party continues and ends with the words<br>
&quot;You can't please everyone so you've got to please yourself.&quot;
